<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-03-01T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-03-01T13:00:00-05:00" n="21" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4/1734: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Acting Chairman of the American Delegation</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-03-01T19:00:00+01:00">March 1,
                                    1933—7 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received March 1—2 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>547. Our 542, February 24, 9 p.m. Yada, Japanese Minister at Berne,
                            acting chief of Japanese disarmament delegation, just called to inform
                            us that he had been to see Henderson, President of the Conference, and
                            informed him that he had received instructions from the Japanese
                            Government that the Japanese delegation would continue to participate in
                            the work of the Disarmament Conference.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>